<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18360404-978">
               <interp inst="t18360404-978" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18360404"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18360404-978" type="date" value="18360404"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18360404-978-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-978-18360404 t18360404-978-offence-1 t18360404-978-verdict-1"></join>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183604040131"></xptr>
               <p>978. <persName id="def1-978-18360404" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-978-18360404" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-978-18360404" type="surname" value="BAKER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-978-18360404" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">GEORGE BAKER</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18360404-978-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18360404-978-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18360404-978-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="theftFromPlace"></interp>for stealing, on the <rs id="t18360404-cd-93" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360404-978-offence-1 t18360404-cd-93"></join>13th of March</rs>, 1 iron gate, value 20<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., the goods of <persName id="t18360404-name-700" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-700" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-700" type="surname" value="ROBERTS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-700" type="given" value="JOSEPH HENRY"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360404-978-offence-1 t18360404-name-700"></join>Joseph Henry Roberts</persName>, and fixed to a building, &amp;c., against the Statute.—2nd <hi rend="smallCaps">COUNT</hi>, stating it to be the property of <persName id="t18360404-name-701">
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-701" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-701" type="surname" value="HAMILTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-701" type="given" value="MARY ANN PIERCE"></interp>Mary Ann Pierce Hamilton</persName>.</rs> 
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360404-name-702" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-702" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-702" type="surname" value="ROBERTS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-702" type="given" value="JOSEPH HENRY"></interp>JOSEPH HENRY ROBERTS</persName>
                  </hi>. I live up a passage, between Nos. 407 and 408, Oxford-street. This gate was at the entrance of that passage—I had seen if safe at twelve o'clock on Saturday night, the 12th of March—it was brought back to me on Wednesday, between eight and nine o'clock, within three quarters of an hour after the prisoner was taken in charge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Who was it brought back by? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> We cannot tell—it was brought after the prisoner was in cus<lb></lb>tody, and put in the passage.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360404-name-703" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-703" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-703" type="surname" value="MARKRAM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-703" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD MARKRAM</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable C</hi>129.) I was on duty on the Sunday night—I met the prisoner at twenty minutes before one o'clock", with this gate—I am sure he is the man I stopped—I can swear that is the gate that he had—I took him back to a light, and examined the gate—it has been mended at the bottom—I took notice of that at the time—the prisoner said he had bought it at a marine-store shop.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> This occurred about one o'clock? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, be<lb></lb>fore one o'clock—I did not take him into custody—he gave me the gate, and, through his appearance, I gave it him back again—I looked at it, and had it in my possession, perhaps a couple or three minutes—I could not recollect any thing about it, or he should not gave gone further with it—he was taken on Tuesday night—I took particular notice of him, in order that if he was taken I should know him again—I took him to a light at a tobacconist's—he went into the tobacconist's and bought a cigar, while I looked at the gate—that is about 150 yards from, where the gate was missed—I took him into custody in Regent-street, with a girl—about half a mile from where the gate was missed—I could swear to the prisoner among ten thousand—he has a very particular look in his eye and his features, that I know him again.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> It was on Sunday night you let him go? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I saw him to Tuesday night, as I was going on duty, at twenty minutes before eight o'clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had he an opportunity of communicating with any body after you took him, till the gate came back? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; there was a girl with him—she went to the watch-house, and then I sent her away, after she had been there two or three minutes—he said, when she was going out, "Go and tell father and brother, you know."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner</hi>. I have got a witness to prove I was at home and in bed at the time they accuse me of the robbery.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360404-name-704" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-704" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-704" type="surname" value="HUGHES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-704" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD HUGHES</persName>
                  </hi>. I keep a tobacconist's shop. I recollect the police<lb></lb>man coming in with the gate, and a person who resembles the prisoner, but I cannot swear to him—I noticed the gate, and can swear to it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360404-name-705" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-705" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-705" type="surname" value="BROWN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-705" type="given" value="CATHERINE"></interp>CATHERINE BROWN</persName>
                  </hi>. I have lodged with the prisoner's mother upwards of two years—he lodges there like wise—that is at No. 21, Vine-street, Inquorpond-street, but they do not go by that name—on Sunday, the 13th of March, I was at home, getting my supper, at half-past ten o'clock, and saw George and Henry Baker go past my room—I was at home at eight o'clock—I saw the prisoner, and his father and mother, sitting down to supper, about a quarter before ten o'clock—I saw the prisoner go past my room at half-past ten o'clock—he wished me good night, and went to their room, which adjoins mine—he had no gate with him—I have known</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183604040132"></xptr>
               <p>him six years—his father is a very severe kind of man, and never suffers his children out of his place—I am positive he would not have allowed him to go out after that.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You saw him pass your door at half-past ten o'clock—that is all you know about it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I did not see him in bed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What was to prevent him going out? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I did not say he did not go out, but his father would not allow him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360404-name-706" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-706" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-706" type="surname" value="BAKER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-706" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE BAKER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the prisoner's father. On Sunday, the 13th of March, I solemnly declare he was in bed at half-past ten o'clock—I went to bed at a quarter before eleven o'clock—I saw him in bed then.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What are you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> A linen-weaver by trade, but I do not work at it—I am a porter to an upholsterer now—I have worked for Edward Stolworthy twelve years, and I am in his employment now.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you and your son sleep in the same bed? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—I was not asleep at twelve o'clock, nor half-past twelve—I must solemnly swear he did not get up, nor did any person in my house—I was awake till half-past twelve o'clock—I was not at one o'clock—my house is situated at No. 21, Lewes-buildings, Liquorpond-street—I have a clock close to my ear—I burn a rush-light, and at half-past twelve o'clock, I looked at clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How do you happen to remember all this so particularly? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> In consequence of his being taken up the Tuesday night after.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Are you certain you were in the room at half-past twelve o'clock? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; he could not have been out without my knowing it—I went to bed at a quarter before eleven o'clock, and about half-past twelve o'clock I dropped off to sleep—when the prisoner was brought up to Marlborough-street, the policeman brought a woman, who was in the tobacconist's shop, and she looked at him, and said that was not the man.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360404-name-707" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-707" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-707" type="surname" value="MARKAM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-707" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD MARKAM</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined</hi>. It is false—there was a woman at the back of me when we stood in the tobacconist's, as I saw there was evidence enough—I did not wish her to speak—she said he was very much like the man, but she could not swear to him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360404-name-708" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-708" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-708" type="surname" value="BAKER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-name-708" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE BAKER</persName>
                  </hi>. When the woman not swear according to his wishes, he would not let her in—I endeavoured to find where she lived—they could find her, but I could not, and they would not let her in.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <rs id="t18360404-978-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18360404-978-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360404-978-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value=""></interp>NOT GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>.</p>
